article.headline: Rockets' thoughts with Rudy T during loss to Sonics
article.linkText: Distracted Rockets see five-game win streak snapped
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Given what's going on with their coach, the Houston Rockets weren't totally focused Tuesday night.
Allen

Lewis

Rashard Lewis scored 25 points and Ray Allen had 23 to lead the Seattle SuperSonics to a 100-94 victory over the Rockets, who were without coach Rudy Tomjanovich for the first time in 11 years. Assistant coach Larry Smith coached the Rockets in place of Tomjanovich, who has been diagnosed with a cancerous tumor on his bladder lining. Tomjanovich plans to rejoin the team during its five-game road trip. "I can't say whether what the coach went through had an effect on us, but I can say that guys were thinking about it,'' said Steve Francis, who led the Rockets with 23 points and 10 assists. He also pulled down nine rebounds to fall just shy of a triple-double. Lewis shot 10-of-20 from the field for Seattle, which has won three of four games to move within four games of Houston and Phoenix for the eighth spot in the Western Conference playoff race. Five Sonics scored in double figures to snap Houston's five-game winning streak. Jerome James and Kevin Ollie came off the bench to score 13 apiece, and Predrag Drobnjak added 11. "We had too many mental lapses in the game,'' said Francis. "You're going to lose when Kevin Ollie scores 13 points and Jerome James scores 13 points. I was involved in some of that. I didn't respect Ollie enough as a shooter and he killed me on the backdoor. I made some mistakes out there, but as a team we need to get better.'' Seattle led by as many as 14 in the fourth quarter after Lewis hit a 17-foot jumper that made it 94-80 with 3:29 left, but the Rockets didn't quit. Glen Rice hit a pair of 3-pointers in the game's final minute that cut into Seattle's lead. The second trimmed the Sonics' advantage to 97-93, but they couldn't get any closer. "I thought we were in position to win the ballgame. We had solid opportunities, but they hit the big 3's in transition,'' said Smith, who was making his debut as a head coach. "They got their hands on some outlet passes which created points for them.'' Cuttino Mobley had 16 and Moochie Norris came off the bench to score 12 of his 14 points in the first half for the Rockets. "We know we need to scrap in order to have an opportunity or a chance to win the game,'' Sonics head coach Nate McMillan said. "These guys came out and scrapped tonight.'' The biggest run by either team came late in the third quarter. After Francis scored six straight points to give the Rockets a 60-58 lead, the Sonics went on a 20-8 run over the final four minutes of the quarter. The Sonics hit four 3-pointers during the stretch. "We knew that they had guys capable of making 3-point shots,'' Smith said. "But I think Ollie and James were the difference in the game.'' With Yao Ming opening the second quarter on the bench, James thrived. With the game tied at 28, Barry lobbed an alley-oop to James for a dunk, his seventh point of the quarter with 8:13 left in the half. Norris' 19-foot jumper snapped a 41-41 tie with 1:45 before the break. On the following possession, Allen responded with a 3-pointer. Norris then made his fifth straight field goal attempt when he hit an 18-footer with 26.1 left. Drobnjak then made a 3-pointer with 1.2 seconds to play, giving the Sonics a 47-43 halftime lead. Seattle made its final three shots of the half from beyond the arc after missing its first six. The Rockets players said they are not sure how big of a distraction the Tomjanovich situation will be for them. "It's tough,'' Francis said. "We are on the verge of a playoff rush and every game is huge for us. Unfortunately that incident happened, but we still have to remain focused with the topic at hand.''

Game notes
Houston activated F Bostjan Nachbar and placed G Tito Maddox on the injured list with a viral infection. ... Rice had gone 30-of-61 on 3-point attempts since coming off the injured list on Feb. 18th. He was 2-of-3 from beyond the arc. ...Lewis has scored at least 24 in the last four games after going seven straight without reaching 20.
